}\n\n'''Lenin Stadium''' ({{lang-ru|\u0421\u0442\u0430\u0434\u0438\u043e\u043d \u0438\u043c\u0435\u043d\u0438 \u041b\u0435\u043d\u0438\u043d\u0430}}) is a multi-use [[stadium]] in [[Khabarovsk]], [[Russia]]. It is currently used mostly for [[association football]] matches and is the home ground of [[FC SKA-Khabarovsk]]. The stadium holds 15,200 people.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lonelyplanet.com/russia/russian-far-east/khabarovsk/entertainment/lenin-stadium/a/poi-ent/1475030/360481|title=Lenin Stadium|last=|first=|date=|website=Lonely Planet|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=15 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://gulfnews.com/world/europe/russia-fears-freezing-out-top-players-1.2128307|title=Russia fears freezing out top players|date=21 November 2017|work=Gulf News|access-date=15 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> It is named after communist revolutionary [[Vladimir Lenin]].\n\n[[Category:Sports venues completed in 1951]]\n[[Category:Football venues in Russia]]\n[[Category:Bandy venues in Russia]]\n[[Category:Sports venues built in the Soviet Union]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Khabarovsk Krai]]\n\n\n{{Russia-sports-venue-stub}}\n", "name_user": "G\u00fcnniX", "label": "safe", "comment": "Reflist", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lenin_Stadium_(Khabarovsk)"}
{"title_page": "James Wright (governor)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name             = James Wright\n|image            = JamesWrightBySoldi.jpg\n|caption          = Portrait by [[Andrea Soldi]]\n|order            = [[List of colonial governors of Georgia|7th Governor of Carolina and Georgia]]\n|office           =\n|term_start       = 1760\n|term_end         = 1776\n|lieutenant       =\n|predecessor      =[[Henry Ellis (governor)|Henry Ellis]]\n|successor        = [[Archibald Campbell (British Army officer)|Archibald Campbell]]\n|birth_date       =  May 8, 1716 \n|birth_place      = [[London]], [[England]] \n|death_date       = {{death date and age|1785|11|20|1716|5|8}}\n|death_place      = London\n|party            =\n|spouse           =  Sarah Maidman (died 1774)\n|children           =  9\n|profession       =  Lawyer, jurist, governor \n|religion         = Catholic\n}}\n\n'''James Wright''' (May 8, 1716 \u2013 November 20, 1785) was an American colonial lawyer and jurist who was the last [[Great Britain|British]] Royal Governor of the [[Province of Georgia]].  He was the only Royal Governor of the [[Thirteen Colonies]] to regain control of his colony during the [[American Revolutionary War]].\n\n== Biography ==\nJames Wright was born in [[London]] to Robert Wright junior, son of Sir  [[Robert Wright (judge, died 1689)|Robert Wright]],  [[Lord Chief Justice of England]], and Isabella Pitts, a widow. In 1730 his father accompanied [[Robert Johnson (governor)|Robert Johnson]] to the [[Province of South Carolina]] and served as its Chief Justice until 1739.  James followed soon after and began the practice of law in [[Charleston, South Carolina|Charleston]].  In 1747 James was named [[Attorney General of South Carolina|colonial attorney-general]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Deaton|first1=Stan|title=James Wright (1716-1785)|url=http://www.georgiaencyclopedia.org/articles/history-archaeology/james-wright-1716-1785|website=New Georgia Encyclopedia|accessdate=14 May 2016}}</ref> He also began amassing plantation lands.\n\nWright returned to London as an agent for the South Carolina colony in 1757. Then, in May 1760, he was named as Lieutenant Governor to [[Henry Ellis (governor)|Henry Ellis]] in Georgia. He returned to America and took up residence in [[Savannah, Georgia]]. When Ellis resigned he was appointed Governor in November 1760.  He was the third, and arguably most popular, Royal Governor of the colony. He sold many of his holdings in South Carolina, acquired land in Georgia, and moved his financial operations as well. With peace temporarily established with the [[France|French]] and [[Spain|Spanish]], he successfully negotiated with the [[First Nations|Indians]] and the Crown to open new lands to development. In his early administration, the new lands and economic improvement fostered the development of the Georgia colony.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Wright|first1=James|title=Answers to queries sent by the Lords of Trade [in] 1761, 1762|url=http://dlg.galileo.usg.edu/zlna/id:jwr001|website=Southeastern Native American Documents, 1730-1842|accessdate=14 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nHis first troubles came with the [[Stamp Act 1765|Stamp Act]] of 1765. But, in spite of efforts by the [[Sons of Liberty]] to block its implementation, Georgia was the only colony to import and actually use the revenue stamps. In 1768, Wright established the 12,000 acre settlement known as [[Wrightsboro, Georgia]]. Wrightsboro was set aside for displaced [[Quakers]] from [[North Carolina]]<ref>[http://www.exploregeorgia.org/listing/2395-historic-wrightsboro Historic Wrightsboro] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140313215224/http://www.exploregeorgia.org/listing/2395-historic-wrightsboro |date=13 March 2014 }}. exploregeorgia.org. Retrieved July 22, 2013.</ref> and became home to [[William Few]] when his family fled North Carolina after their farm had been burned and [[James Few]], William's brother had been hanged without a trial. As the [[American Revolution]] gathered momentum, Georgia remained the most [[Loyalist (American Revolution)|loyal]] colony\u2014due in part to its recent settlement, with many residents having direct ties through [[kinship]] in Great Britain, and, in part as well, to Wright's able administration. Georgia did not send delegates to the [[First Continental Congress]] in 1774. That same year saw the death of his wife, Sarah.\n\nBy 1775, the revolutionary spirit had reached Georgia through the ''[[Committees of correspondence]]'' and he dismissed the assembly. But a revolutionary congress met that summer in Savannah and elected delegates to the [[Second Continental Congress]]. Then, in early 1776, following [[Battle of the Rice Boats|the arrival of a small British fleet]], rebel forces entered his home and briefly took him prisoner. Wright escaped on February 11, 1776, via [[Bonaventure Plantation]] and with the assistance of two compatriots, Colonel John Mullryne and [[Josiah Tattnall, Sr.|Josiah Tattnall]],<ref>[https://www.telfair.org/article/bonaventure-a-historical-sketch/ \"BONAVENTURE: A HISTORICAL SKETCH\"] - [[Telfair Museums]], July 27, 2018</ref> to the safety of HMS ''Scarborough'', and sent a letter to his council. The congress and the Council adjourned without answering him.\n\nFor a time, Wright continued negotiations. He was even able to trade with the rebels to keep his offshore troops and ships supplied. But the differences continued to escalate. When his attempt to retake Savannah with naval forces failed, he returned to England.\n\nBy 1778, Governor Wright convinced the government to lend him enough troops to once again attempt to take Savannah. After some short but sharp fights, he [[Capture of Savannah|regained control of Savannah]] on December 29, 1778. While never fully in control of the state, he did restore large areas within Georgia to colonial rule, making this the only colony that was regained by the British once they had been expelled. He led a successful defense against several American and French attempts to capture the city. When the war was lost, he withdrew on July 11, 1782 and retired to England.\n\nWright's extensive properties were seized by the revolutionary governments in South Carolina and Georgia. He died in London, and is interred at [[Westminster Abbey]].\n\n== Wright's offspring==\nJames F. Cook in his book ''The Governors of Georgia 1754-2004'' states that Sir James Wright (1716-1785) and Sarah Maidman (died 1763) had nine children. They were:\n\n* Sir James Wright (1747&ndash;1816), the 2nd Baronet. He married Sarah Williamson Smith,<ref>''Letters of Robert Mackay to His Wife: Written from Ports in America and England 1795-1816'', by Walter Charlton Hartridge</ref> daughter of Captain John Smith and Elizabeth Williamson (other sources such as Burke's Peerage of 1833 incorrectly call her Mary Smith, daughter of John Smith, a former governor of South Carolina) and died without issue.\n* Sarah (1744&ndash;?), who went with her father Sir James Wright and her brothers James, Alexander and Charles to Jamaica with other family members, where they were granted land,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://jamaicanfamilysearch.com/Samples2/Americanloyalists.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2013-06-22 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131121043729/http://jamaicanfamilysearch.com/Samples2/Americanloyalists.htm |archivedate=2013-11-21 }}</ref> and later to England to join her father, where she married William Bartram of Norfolk, a Jacobite.\n* Alexander (1751&ndash;?), who was a Loyalist and lost his America estates. He moved to Jamaica and married Elizabeth Izard, daughter of John Izard and niece of [[Congressman]] [[Ralph Izard]]. He was the father of the Sir James Alexander Wright, the 3rd Baronet<ref>''A General and Heraldic Dictionary of the Peerage and Baronetage of the British Empire, Volume 2'', by John Burke (1833)</ref> and of John Izard Wright, the father of Sir John Wright, the 4th Baronet.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Kimber|first1=Edward|title=The baronetage of England : containing a genealogical and historical account of all the English baronets now existing|date=1771|publisher=G. Woodfall|location=London|url=https://archive.org/details/baronetageofengl01wott|accessdate=14 May 2016}}</ref>\n* Charles\n* Ann (1749&ndash;?), who married British Admiral [[James Wallace (Royal Navy officer)|James Wallace]]\n* Elizabeth\n* Charlotte\n* Mary (1742&ndash;1763)\n* Isabella, who married General Thomas Barrow in 1757\n\n==External links==\n* {{cite web|title=Answers to queries sent by the Lords of Trade [in] 1761, 1762 / Governor James Wright|url=http://dbs.galib.uga.edu/cgi-bin/write_stats.cgi?stattype=fulltext&dbscode=ZLNA&format=djv&redirect=http://purl.galileo.usg.edu/nativeamericandocs/djv/jwr001a0.djv|website=Southeastern Native American Documents, 1730-1842|publisher=Digital Library of Georgia|accessdate=13 February 2018}}\n\n== References ==\n*{{cite DNB|wstitle=Wright, James (1716-1785)|volume=63}}\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wright, James}}\n[[Category:1716 births]]\n[[Category:1785 deaths]]\n[[Category:British emigrants to the Thirteen Colonies]]\n[[Category:British officials in the American Revolution]]\n[[Category:Burials at Westminster Abbey]]\n[[Category:Colonial governors of Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:Loyalists in the American Revolution from Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:Politicians from London]]\n[[Category:Lawyers from London]]\n[[Category:South Carolina Attorneys General]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name             = James Wright\n|image            = JamesWrightBySoldi.jpg\n|caption          = Portrait by [[Andrea Soldi]]\n|order            = [[List of colonial governors of Georgia|7th Governor of Carolina and Georgia]]\n|office           =\n|term_start       = 1760\n|term_end         = 1776\n|lieutenant       =\n|predecessor      =[[Henry Ellis (governor)|Henry Ellis]]\n|successor        = [[Archibald Campbell (British Army officer)|Archibald Campbell]]\n|birth_date       =  May 8, 1716 \n|birth_place      = [[London]], [[England]] \n|death_date       = {{death date and age|1785|11|20|1716|5|8}}\n|death_place      = London\n|party            =\n|spouse           =  Sarah Maidman (died 1774)\n|children           =  9\n|profession       =  Lawyer, jurist, governor \n|religion         = Catholic\n}}\n\n'''James Wright''' (May 8, 1716 \u2013 November 20, 1785) was an American colonial lawyer and jurist who was the last [[Great Britain|British]] Royal Governor of the [[Province of Georgia]].  He was the only Royal Governor of the [[Thirteen Colonies]] to regain control of his colony during the [[American Revolutionary War]].\n\n== Biography ==\nJames Wright was born in [[London]] to Robert Wright junior, son of Sir  [[Robert Wright (judge, died 1689)|Robert Wright]],  [[Lord Chief Justice of England]], and Isabella Pitts, a widow. In 1730 his father accompanied [[Robert Johnson (governor)|Robert Johnson]] to the [[Province of South Carolina]] and served as its Chief Justice until 1739.  James followed soon after and began the practice of law in [[Charleston, South Carolina|Charleston]].  In 1747 James was named [[Attorney General of South Carolina|colonial attorney-general]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Deaton|first1=Stan|title=James Wright (1716-1785)|url=http://www.georgiaencyclopedia.org/articles/history-archaeology/james-wright-1716-1785|website=New Georgia Encyclopedia|accessdate=14 May 2016}}</ref> He also began amassing plantation lands.\n\nWright returned to London as an agent for the South Carolina colony in 1757. Then, in May 1760, he was named as Lieutenant Governor to [[Henry Ellis (governor)|Henry Ellis]] in Georgia. He returned to America and took up residence in [[Savannah, Georgia]]. When Ellis resigned he was appointed Governor in November 1760.  He was the third, and arguably most popular, Royal Governor of the colony. He sold many of his holdings in South Carolina, acquired land in Georgia, and moved his financial operations as well. With peace temporarily established with the [[France|French]] and [[Spain|Spanish]], he successfully negotiated with the [[First Nations|Indians]] and the Crown to open new lands to development. In his early administration, the new lands and economic improvement fostered the development of the Georgia colony.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Wright|first1=James|title=Answers to queries sent by the Lords of Trade [in] 1761, 1762|url=http://dlg.galileo.usg.edu/zlna/id:jwr001|website=Southeastern Native American Documents, 1730-1842|accessdate=14 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nHis first troubles came with the [[Stamp Act 1765|Stamp Act]] of 1765. But, in spite of efforts by the [[Sons of Liberty]] to block its implementation, Georgia was the only colony to import and actually use the revenue stamps. In 1768, Wright established the 12,000 acre settlement known as [[Wrightsboro, Georgia]]. Wrightsboro was set aside for displaced [[Quakers]] from [[North Carolina]]<ref>[http://www.exploregeorgia.org/listing/2395-historic-wrightsboro Historic Wrightsboro] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140313215224/http://www.exploregeorgia.org/listing/2395-historic-wrightsboro |date=13 March 2014 }}. exploregeorgia.org. Retrieved July 22, 2013.</ref> and became home to [[William Few]] when his family fled North Carolina after their farm had been burned and [[James Few]], William's brother had been hanged without a trial. As the [[American Revolution]] gathered momentum, Georgia remained the most [[Loyalist (American Revolution)|loyal]] colony\u2014due in part to its recent settlement, with many residents having direct ties through [[kinship]] in Great Britain, and, in part as well, to Wright's able administration. Georgia did not send delegates to the [[First Continental Congress]] in 1774. That same year saw the death of his wife, Sarah.\n\nBy 1775, the revolutionary spirit had reached Georgia through the ''[[Committees of correspondence]]'' and he dismissed the assembly. But a revolutionary congress met that summer in Savannah and elected delegates to the [[Second Continental Congress]]. Then, in early 1776, following [[Battle of the Rice Boats|the arrival of a small British fleet]], rebel forces entered his home and briefly took him prisoner. Wright escaped on February 11, 1776, via [[Bonaventure Plantation]] and with the assistance of two compatriots, Colonel John Mullryne and [[Josiah Tattnall, Sr.|Josiah Tattnall]],<ref>[https://www.telfair.org/article/bonaventure-a-historical-sketch/ \"BONAVENTURE: A HISTORICAL SKETCH\"] - [[Telfair Museums]], July 27, 2018</ref> to the safety of HMS ''Scarborough'', and sent a letter to his council. The congress and the Council adjourned without answering him.\n\nFor a time, Wright continued negotiations. He was even able to trade with the rebels to keep his offshore troops and ships supplied. But the differences continued to escalate. When his attempt to retake Savannah with naval forces failed, he returned to England.\n\nBy 1778, Governor Wright convinced the government to lend him enough troops to once again attempt to take Savannah. After some short but sharp fights, he [[Capture of Savannah|regained control of Savannah]] on December 29, 1778. While never fully in control of the state, he did restore large areas within Georgia to colonial rule, making this the only colony that was regained by the British once they had been expelled. He led a successful defense against several American and French attempts to capture the city. When the war was lost, he withdrew on July 11, 1782 and retired to England.\n\nWright's extensive properties were seized by the revolutionary governments in South Carolina and Georgia. He died in London, and is interred at [[Westminster Abbey]].\n\n== Wright's offspring==\nJames F. Cook in his book ''The Governors of Georgia 1754-2004'' states that Sir James Wright (1716-1785) and Sarah Maidman (died 1763) had nine children. They were:\n\n* Sir James Wright (1747&ndash;1816), the 2nd Baronet. He married Sarah Williamson Smith,<ref>''Letters of Robert Mackay to His Wife: Written from Ports in America and England 1795-1816'', by Walter Charlton Hartridge</ref> daughter of Captain John Smith and Elizabeth Williamson (other sources such as Burke's Peerage of 1833 incorrectly call her Mary Smith, daughter of John Smith, a former governor of South Carolina) and died without issue.\n* Sarah (1744&ndash;?), who went with her father Sir James Wright and her brothers James, Alexander and Charles to Jamaica with other family members, where they were granted land,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://jamaicanfamilysearch.com/Samples2/Americanloyalists.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2013-06-22 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131121043729/http://jamaicanfamilysearch.com/Samples2/Americanloyalists.htm |archivedate=2013-11-21 }}</ref> and later to England to join her father, where she married William Bartram of Norfolk, a Jacobite.\n* Alexander (1751&ndash;?), who was a Loyalist and lost his America estates. He moved to Jamaica and married Elizabeth Izard, daughter of John Izard and niece of [[Congressman]] [[Ralph Izard]]. He was the father of the Sir James Alexander Wright, the 3rd Baronet<ref>''A General and Heraldic Dictionary of the Peerage and Baronetage of the British Empire, Volume 2'', by John Burke (1833)</ref> and of John Izard Wright, the father of Sir John Wright, the 4th Baronet.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Kimber|first1=Edward|title=The baronetage of England : containing a genealogical and historical account of all the English baronets now existing|date=1771|publisher=G. Woodfall|location=London|url=https://archive.org/details/baronetageofengl01wott|accessdate=14 May 2016}}</ref>\n* Charles\n* Ann (1749&ndash;?), who married British Admiral [[James Wallace (Royal Navy officer)|James Wallace]]\n* Elizabeth\n* Charlotte\n* Mary (1742&ndash;1763, at sea with her mother)\n* Isabella, who married General Thomas Barrow in 1757\n\n==External links==\n* {{cite web|title=Answers to queries sent by the Lords of Trade [in] 1761, 1762 / Governor James Wright|url=http://dbs.galib.uga.edu/cgi-bin/write_stats.cgi?stattype=fulltext&dbscode=ZLNA&format=djv&redirect=http://purl.galileo.usg.edu/nativeamericandocs/djv/jwr001a0.djv|website=Southeastern Native American Documents, 1730-1842|publisher=Digital Library of Georgia|accessdate=13 February 2018}}\n\n== References ==\n*{{cite DNB|wstitle=Wright, James (1716-1785)|volume=63}}\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wright, James}}\n[[Category:1716 births]]\n[[Category:1785 deaths]]\n[[Category:British emigrants to the Thirteen Colonies]]\n[[Category:British officials in the American Revolution]]\n[[Category:Burials at Westminster Abbey]]\n[[Category:Colonial governors of Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:Loyalists in the American Revolution from Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:Politicians from London]]\n[[Category:Lawyers from London]]\n[[Category:South Carolina Attorneys General]]\n", "name_user": "Seasider53", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eWright's offspring", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/James_Wright_(governor)"}
{"title_page": "Compensation (film)", "text_new": "{{Infobox film\n| name           = ''Compensation''\n| image          = Compensation (2000 film).jpg\n| image size     = \n| caption        = ''Compensation'' film poster\n| director       = [[Zeinabu irene Davis]]\n| producer       = Zeinabu irene Davis\n| writer         = Marc Arthur Ch\u00e9ry\n| story          = \n| based on       = <!-- {{based on the poem|Lyrics of Sunshine and Shadhow|Paul Laurence Dunbar}} -->\n| narrator       = \n| starring       = Michelle A. Banks and [[John Earl Jelks]]\n| music          = [[Reginald R. Robinson]] and Atiba Y. Jali\n| cinematography = Pierre H. L. Desir, Jr.\n| editing        = Zeinabu irene Davis and Dana Briscoe\n| studio         = \n| distributor    = Women Make Movies\n| released       = {{Film date|1999|6|14|Atlanta Film & Video Festival}}{{Citation needed|date=May 2019}}\n| runtime        = 92 minutes\n| country        = United States\n| language       = [[English language|English]], [[Sign language]]\n| budget         = $125,000\n| gross          = \n}}\n'''Compensation''' is a 1999 independent film co-edited, produced and directed by [[Zeinabu irene Davis]] and written by March Arthur Ch\u00e9ry, about a young African American couple at the beginning and end of the twentieth century. It stars Michelle A. Banks and [[John Earl Jelks]] in the leading roles. The film was shot throughout [[Chicago]]<ref name=\"University of Buffalo, Department of African American Studies\">[http://wings.buffalo.edu/cas/aas/] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100612235618/http://wings.buffalo.edu/cas/aas/ |date=2010-06-12 }}, University of Buffalo, Department of African American Studies</ref> beginning July 1993 and wrapped up early August.\n\nThe film premiered at the 2000 [[Sundance Film Festival]] and ran in the Dramatic Feature category.<ref name=\"Sundance Film Festival\">[http://history.sundance.org/films/2334], Sundance Institute Archives.</ref> The film was screened in [[San Diego, California]] at the [[Museum of Photographic Arts]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ucsdnews.ucsd.edu/newsrel/soc/dzdavispremiere.htm|title=UCSD Social Sciences|publisher=Ucsdnews.ucsd.edu|date=23 May 2000|accessdate=1 January 2012}}</ref> It was also screened at [[Independent Feature Project|IFP]] the Independent Film Market in [[New York City|New York, New York]] and the [[Pan African Film Festival]] in [[Los Angeles]].\n\n==Plot==\nInspired by a 1906 poem from early African American writer, [[Paul Laurence Dunbar]], the unique drama explores aspects of Black culture in both turn of the century and present day Chicago in two parallel love stories, both about the relationship between a deaf woman and a hearing man. The narrative revolves about two couples, Malindy and Arthur, and Malaika and Nico, respectively taking place at the beginning and end of the twentieth century. Both pairs revel in the splendor or romance and a possible lifetime commitment only to be forced to deal with the dreaded disease of their difference times: [[tuberculosis]] and [[AIDS]]. The multi-layered film tackles various issues that arise in the relationship of the \"mixed\" couples.<ref name=\"Press Release\">Compensation Press Release.</ref>\n\n==Cast==\n*Michelle A. Banks as Malindy Brown and Malaika Brown\n*[[John Earl Jelks]] as Arthur Jones and Nico Jones\n*Christopher Smith as William Young and dancer\n*K. Lynn Stephens as Aminata Brown\n*Nirvana Cobb as Tildy\n*Kevin L. Davis as Tyrone\n\n==Production==\n===Filming===\nThe entire film was shot in Chicago, Illinois to play a tribute to the director's previous residence and to expose the audience to the beautiful city. Well-known filming locations within Chicago.<ref name=\"Press Release\"/>\n*Ephphatha Evangelical Lutheran Church of the Deaf\n*Chicago Public Library, Legler Branch\n*Indiana Dunes National Lakeshore\n*Northwestern University, Evanston\n*Salsedo Press, Chicago\n*The Warehouse, Chicago\n\n===Music===\n[[Reginald R. Robinson]], a noted ragtime composer and performer, served as the film's period music score composer. He incorporated the piano and mandolin into all his compositions for the film.\n\nAtiba Y. Jali, served as the contemporary music score composer. He used instruments that are not as common such as the balafou, [[berimbau]] and [[yidaki]] but also included the drums and flute.\n\n===Film Festivals===\n*[[Sundance Film Festival]]<ref name=\"film festivals\">[http://www.wmm.com/filmcatalog/makers/fm26.shtml], http://www.wmm.com/filmcatalog/makers/fm26.shtml.</ref>\n*[[Toronto International Film Festival]]<ref name=\"film festivals\"/>\n*[[Atlanta Film and Video Festival]]<ref name=\"film festivals\"/>\n\n==Critical Reception==\nThe film was overall well received by many notable film critics and enjoyed a positive reception from both critics and moviegoers.\n*Kevin Thomas of the Los Angeles Times hailed ''Compensation'' \"beautiful and poignant\" and \"illuminating and captivating\".<ref name=\"Kevin Thomas\">[Kevin Thomas, Los Angeles Times: 'Compensation' Rewards, 24 February 2000], Los Angeles Times.</ref>\n*Ian Grey of City Paper, Baltimore's Free Alternative Weekly, praised ''Compensation'' as \"brilliant\".<ref name=\"Ian Grey\">[http://www2.citypaper.com/film/review.asp?rid=5893 City Paper, Baltimore's Free Alternative Weekly].</ref>\n*David Elliott of The San Diego Union Tribune called the film a \"classy achievement\".<ref name=\"test\">David Elliott, The San Diego Union Tribune: The Weekly Guide, 'Compensation' speaks in a visual language, 1\u20137 June 2000.</ref>\n*[[Roger Ebert]] praised the film as \"dreamy, atmosphere reveries, rich in humor and social observation\" as well as \"enchanting\".<ref name=\"Chicago Sun times\">[Roger Ebert, Chicago Sun-Times: Showcase, 25 January 2000].</ref>\n*Rick Lyman of The New York Times noted the film is \"structurally daring\".<ref name=\"The NY Times\">[Rick Lyman, The New York Times: Taking a Chance, 4 February 2000]</ref>\n*Greg Dimitriadis called the film \"...a powerful film. It is boldly experimental. Illness and death are presented as forces that persons cannot control. The death of a loved one is blunted by the gift of love itself. That gift compensates for life\u2019s losses. In showing this, Davis\u2019s film brings great dignity and respect to the situations of African American women and men. At the same time, her film honors African American culture and history.\"<ref name=\"sage\">[http://csc.sagepub.com/content/3/1/22.full.pdf].</ref>\n*[[Elizabeth Alexander (poet)|Elizabeth Alexander]] noted the poem that inspired the film \"should move this very contemporary filmmaker narratively to the past but technically forward to innovation\".<ref name=\"book\">[https://books.google.com/books?id=b_mXa0NV9UUC&printsec=frontcover&dq=power+and+possibility+elizabeth+alexander&source=bl&ots=hqC8N3yLSx&sig=HOAvP5pieCeHOmpOcqVm96rpFxc&hl=en&ei=LP7_TJ7HCIO4sQOg3pWwCw&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&sqi=2&ved=0CBMQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=zeinabu%20irene%20davis&f=false].</ref>\n\n==Release==\n===Distribution===\nThe film is available on [[VHS]] and [[DVD]] distributed by [[Women Make Movies]].<ref>http://www.wmm.com/filmcatalog/makers/fm26.shtml.</ref>\n\n==Awards and accolades==\n1999 Gordon Parks Directing Award, Independent Feature Project, New York<ref name=\"WMM\">[http://www.wmm.com/filmcatalog/makers/fm26.shtml], Women Make Movies website.</ref>\n\n1999 Reel Black Award for Outstanding Film, Black Film and Video Network<ref name=\"Press Release\"/>\n\n15th Annual IFP/West Independent Spirit Awards, Nominated Best First Feature Film Under $500,000<ref name=\"Press Release\"/>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of films featuring the deaf and hard of hearing]]\n\n==References==\n<!--- See http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Footnotes on how to create references using tags which will then appear here automatically -->\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.wmm.com/filmcatalog/pages/c607.shtml/ WMM.com]\n*[http://arquivo.pt/wayback/20090715051031/http://communication.ucsd.edu/PeoplePages/ZeinabuDavis.html communication.ucsd.edu]\n*[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0223027/ IMdB]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Compensation (Film)}}\n[[Category:2000 films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American independent films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox film\n| name           = ''Compensation''\n| image          = Compensation (2000 film).jpg\n| image size     = \n| caption        = ''Compensation'' film poster\n| director       = [[Zeinabu irene Davis]]\n| producer       = Zeinabu irene Davis\n| writer         = Marc Arthur Ch\u00e9ry\n| story          = \n| based on       = <!-- {{based on the poem|Lyrics of Sunshine and Shadhow|Paul Laurence Dunbar}} -->\n| narrator       = \n| starring       = Michelle A. Banks and [[John Earl Jelks]]\n| music          = [[Reginald R. Robinson]] and Atiba Y. Jali\n| cinematography = Pierre H. L. Desir, Jr.\n| editing        = Zeinabu irene Davis and Dana Briscoe\n| studio         = \n| distributor    = Women Make Movies\n| released       = {{Film date|1999|6|14|Atlanta Film & Video Festival}}{{Citation needed|date=May 2019}}\n| runtime        = 92 minutes\n| country        = United States\n| language       = [[English language|English]], [[Sign language]]\n| budget         = $125,000\n| gross          = \n}}\n'''Compensation''' is a 1999 independent film co-edited, produced and directed by [[Zeinabu irene Davis]] and written by March Arthur Ch\u00e9ry, about a young African American couple at the beginning and end of the twentieth century. It stars Michelle A. Banks and [[John Earl Jelks]] in the leading roles. The film was shot throughout [[Chicago]]<ref name=\"University of Buffalo, Department of African American Studies\">[http://wings.buffalo.edu/cas/aas/] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100612235618/http://wings.buffalo.edu/cas/aas/ |date=2010-06-12 }}, University of Buffalo, Department of African American Studies</ref> beginning July 1993 and wrapped up early August.\n\nThe film premiered at the 2000 [[Sundance Film Festival]] and ran in the Dramatic Feature category.<ref name=\"Sundance Film Festival\">[http://history.sundance.org/films/2334], Sundance Institute Archives.</ref> The film was screened in [[San Diego, California]] at the [[Museum of Photographic Arts]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ucsdnews.ucsd.edu/newsrel/soc/dzdavispremiere.htm|title=UCSD Social Sciences|publisher=Ucsdnews.ucsd.edu|date=23 May 2000|accessdate=1 January 2012}}</ref> It was also screened at [[Independent Feature Project|IFP]] the Independent Film Market in [[New York City|New York, New York]] and the [[Pan African Film Festival]] in [[Los Angeles]].\n\n==Plot==\nInspired by a 1906 poem from early African American writer, [[Paul Laurence Dunbar]], the unique drama explores aspects of Black culture in both turn of the century and present day Chicago in two parallel love stories, both about the relationship between a deaf woman and a hearing man. The narrative revolves about two couples, Malindy and Arthur, and Malaika and Nico, respectively taking place at the beginning and end of the twentieth century. Both pairs revel in the splendor or romance and a possible lifetime commitment only to be forced to deal with the dreaded disease of their difference times: [[tuberculosis]] and [[AIDS]]. The multi-layered film tackles various issues that arise in the relationship of the \"mixed\" couples.<ref name=\"Press Release\">Compensation Press Release.</ref>\n\n==Cast==\n*Michelle A. Banks as Malindy Brown and Malaika Brown\n*[[John Earl Jelks]] as Arthur Jones and Nico Jones\n*Christopher Smith as William Young and dancer\n*K. Lynn Stephens as Aminata Brown\n*Nirvana Cobb as Tildy\n*Kevin L. Davis as Tyrone\n\n==Production==\n===Filming===\nThe entire film was shot in Chicago, Illinois to play a tribute to the director's previous residence and to expose the audience to the beautiful city. Well-known filming locations within Chicago.<ref name=\"Press Release\"/>\n*Ephphatha Evangelical Lutheran Church of the Deaf\n*Chicago Public Library, Legler Branch\n*Indiana Dunes National Lakeshore\n*Northwestern University, Evanston\n*Salsedo Press, Chicago\n*The Warehouse, Chicago\n\n===Music===\n[[Reginald R. Robinson]], a noted ragtime composer and performer, served as the film's period music score composer. He incorporated the piano and mandolin into all his compositions for the film.\n\nAtiba Y. Jali, served as the contemporary music score composer. He used instruments that are not as common such as the balafou, [[berimbau]] and [[yidaki]] but also included the drums and flute.\n\n===Film Festivals===\n*[[Sundance Film Festival]]<ref name=\"film festivals\">[http://www.wmm.com/filmcatalog/makers/fm26.shtml], http://www.wmm.com/filmcatalog/makers/fm26.shtml.</ref>\n*[[Toronto International Film Festival]]<ref name=\"film festivals\"/>\n*[[Atlanta Film and Video Festival]]<ref name=\"film festivals\"/>\n\n==Reception==\n===Critical Response===\nThe film was overall well received by many notable film critics and enjoyed a positive reception from both critics and moviegoers.\n*Kevin Thomas of the Los Angeles Times hailed ''Compensation'' \"beautiful and poignant\" and \"illuminating and captivating\".<ref name=\"Kevin Thomas\">[Kevin Thomas, Los Angeles Times: 'Compensation' Rewards, 24 February 2000], Los Angeles Times.</ref>\n*Ian Grey of City Paper, Baltimore's Free Alternative Weekly, praised ''Compensation'' as \"brilliant\".<ref name=\"Ian Grey\">[http://www2.citypaper.com/film/review.asp?rid=5893 City Paper, Baltimore's Free Alternative Weekly].</ref>\n*David Elliott of The San Diego Union Tribune called the film a \"classy achievement\".<ref name=\"test\">David Elliott, The San Diego Union Tribune: The Weekly Guide, 'Compensation' speaks in a visual language, 1\u20137 June 2000.</ref>\n*[[Roger Ebert]] praised the film as \"dreamy, atmosphere reveries, rich in humor and social observation\" as well as \"enchanting\".<ref name=\"Chicago Sun times\">[Roger Ebert, Chicago Sun-Times: Showcase, 25 January 2000].</ref>\n*Rick Lyman of The New York Times noted the film is \"structurally daring\".<ref name=\"The NY Times\">[Rick Lyman, The New York Times: Taking a Chance, 4 February 2000]</ref>\n*Greg Dimitriadis called the film \"...a powerful film. It is boldly experimental. Illness and death are presented as forces that persons cannot control. The death of a loved one is blunted by the gift of love itself. That gift compensates for life\u2019s losses. In showing this, Davis\u2019s film brings great dignity and respect to the situations of African American women and men. At the same time, her film honors African American culture and history.\"<ref name=\"sage\">[http://csc.sagepub.com/content/3/1/22.full.pdf].</ref>\n*[[Elizabeth Alexander (poet)|Elizabeth Alexander]] noted the poem that inspired the film \"should move this very contemporary filmmaker narratively to the past but technically forward to innovation\".<ref name=\"book\">[https://books.google.com/books?id=b_mXa0NV9UUC&printsec=frontcover&dq=power+and+possibility+elizabeth+alexander&source=bl&ots=hqC8N3yLSx&sig=HOAvP5pieCeHOmpOcqVm96rpFxc&hl=en&ei=LP7_TJ7HCIO4sQOg3pWwCw&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&sqi=2&ved=0CBMQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=zeinabu%20irene%20davis&f=false].</ref>\n\n==Release==\n===Distribution===\nThe film is available on [[VHS]] and [[DVD]] distributed by [[Women Make Movies]].<ref>http://www.wmm.com/filmcatalog/makers/fm26.shtml.</ref>\n\n==Awards and accolades==\n1999 Gordon Parks Directing Award, Independent Feature Project, New York<ref name=\"WMM\">[http://www.wmm.com/filmcatalog/makers/fm26.shtml], Women Make Movies website.</ref>\n\n1999 Reel Black Award for Outstanding Film, Black Film and Video Network<ref name=\"Press Release\"/>\n\n15th Annual IFP/West Independent Spirit Awards, Nominated Best First Feature Film Under $500,000<ref name=\"Press Release\"/>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of films featuring the deaf and hard of hearing]]\n\n==References==\n<!--- See http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Footnotes on how to create references using tags which will then appear here automatically -->\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.wmm.com/filmcatalog/pages/c607.shtml/ WMM.com]\n*[http://arquivo.pt/wayback/20090715051031/http://communication.ucsd.edu/PeoplePages/ZeinabuDavis.html communication.ucsd.edu]\n*[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0223027/ IMdB]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Compensation (Film)}}\n[[Category:2000 films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American independent films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n", "name_user": "Campesinoster", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReception:Critical", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Compensation_(film)"}
